<br>
What the heck is wrong with a private company wanting to make more profit?  Greedy?  I suppose, but it's the oil the runs the engine of our world economy.  It's how folks have jobs, and get raises, and can buy entertainment like, well, EQ.  When profit doesn't happen, folks lose jobs, don't get raises, and have scale back their entertainment expenses.  <br>
<br>
Is EQ a food, or medicine that folks are reliant upon for survival?  Even those items are sold based on their market return.  <br>
<br>
If they see a potential source of extra revenue they aren't supposed to seize it?  What's the basis for your sense of this entitlement?  <br>
<br>
Alternatively, they could simply jack up the monthly subscription price.  Would you like that better?<br>
<br>
If you disagree with their business model, then that's a more legitimate argument, but they don't owe anybody anything more than what they already provide.  I've made the decision as a consumer that it is a great value, and I love their product.  <br>
<br>
Certainly they've analyzed the business model and determined they will make more money.  Attacking the &quot;morality&quot; of their business determination for assigning *game* prices is nutty, imho.  I don't buy the &quot;bait and switch&quot; argument either.  Simply because a premium service is offered doesn't mean the non-premium service is illegal.  Hello first class travel v. coach travel.  <br>
<br>
In the end that's good, because hopefully the folks on the Legends servers will pay for extra content that will work its way onto the regular servers.  I won't be paying $40 a month for EQ, but god bless the folks who do.  <br>
<br>
If you disagree, then cancel.  Folks do have an odd sense of entitlement at times.  <br>
